NEW += '                        <div class="topic-meta">35 problems &middot; 5 stages &middot; dp[v][0/1], rerooting two-pass, dp[v][k] knapsack, centroid decomp, DSU on tree, virtual tree</div>\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
NEW += '                </div>\n'
NEW += '                <div class="topic-body">\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why This Topic Matters:</strong> Tree DP is the intersection of dynamic programming and tree traversal. It solves problems where the answer at every node is a function of answers from its children &mdash; optimal substructure arises from the tree\'s hierarchical decomposition. The core invariant: once every subtree is solved, the parent can be solved in O(merge_cost) time and the global answer is assembled bottom-up in a single post-order traversal. This appears in every top-tier interview because it tests three skills simultaneously: (1) identifying optimal substructure in a recursive tree structure, (2) designing a correct DP state over a non-linear topology, and (3) analysing and optimising the merge cost across child DPs. In competitive programming it escalates to tree knapsack (O(n&sup2;) &rarr; O(n log n) with careful merge ordering), rerooting DP (computing answers for every possible root in O(n)), and DP on forests extracted from interval containment or centroid decomposition.</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="info-box">Every node is the CEO of its own company (its subtree). The CEO\'s performance review (dp[v]) is computed entirely from the performance reviews of direct reports. The post-order DFS is the HR department walking the org chart bottom-up. The two-pass rerooting DP is a second HR walk top-down, where the CEO also considers feedback from above. The tree knapsack is the CEO allocating a budget of K headcount across all teams.<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>How this mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Simplest form:</strong> dp[v] = single scalar; bottom-up accumulation. No choice; just aggregate from children.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; What changes:</strong> ONE choice per node: include or exclude. dp[v][0/1] &mdash; two states; the merge chooses which child state to consume.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 3 &mdash; What expands:</strong> State gains a budget dimension k. dp[v][k] = best answer using exactly k nodes/edges in subtree. Merging two children\'s dp[][j] and dp[][k&minus;j] becomes a convolution.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 4 &mdash; What is hidden:</strong> The problem doesn\'t mention trees. The structure is implied by intervals, dependencies, or recursion. Recognising the hidden tree structure IS the solve.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>Stage 5 &mdash; What is optimised:</strong> The O(n&sup2;) knapsack merge or O(n) per-query rerooting is too slow. Small-to-large merging, virtual trees, or precomputed prefix/suffix DP arrays bring this to O(n log n).\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariants / Proof Sketches</div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="core-box">\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Invariant 1: Post-Order Optimality</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Invariant:</em> In a post-order traversal, when node v is processed, dp[c] is fully correct for every child c of v.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> By strong induction on subtree size. Base: leaves are trivial. Inductive step: when v is processed, every child c has smaller subtree size; by inductive hypothesis dp[c] is correct. Therefore dp[v] = f(dp[c1], dp[c2], ..., val[v]) is computed from correct inputs. &#9633;<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Invariant 2: Rerooting Transition Correctness</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Invariant:</em> ans[v] = ans[parent(v)] + (n &minus; sz[v]) &minus; sz[v], where sz[v] = subtree size rooted at node 0.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> When re-rooting from parent to v: every node inside sz[v] gets 1 closer (&minus;sz[v]), every node outside (n &minus; sz[v]) gets 1 farther. Net = (n &minus; sz[v]) &minus; sz[v]. Since ans[parent] was correct by induction, ans[v] is correct. &#9633;<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Invariant 3: Tree Knapsack O(n&sup2;) Bound via Pair Argument</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> For any pair (u, w) of nodes in different subtrees of their LCA, they contribute O(1) to exactly ONE merge at their LCA. There are at most C(n,2) such pairs, so total merge cost = O(n&sup2;). &#9633;<br><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <strong>Invariant 4: Small-to-Large O(n log n)</strong><br>\n'
NEW += '                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> Each time element e moves from S_small to S_large, the set containing e at least doubles. From size 1, an element can double at most log&sub2;n times. Total operations = O(n log n). &#9633;\n'
NEW += '                    </div>\n'
NEW += '                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>\n'
